excerpt: Gothic cathedral with vast stained-glass windows, interactive Undercroft exhibition & tower tours.
detail_description: York Minster, also known as The Cathedral and Metropolitical Church of Saint Peter in York, is a magnificent Gothic cathedral with impressive stained-glass windows. Visitors can explore the interactive Undercroft exhibition to learn about the cathedral's history and construction. Tower tours are available for those who want to climb up and enjoy breathtaking views of the city.
name: York Minster
address: Deangate, York, YO1 7HH, United Kingdom

excerpt: A fully reconstructed Viking village complete with the sights and smells, and an adjoining museum.
detail_description: Step into the world of the Vikings at Jorvik Viking Centre, where you can explore a fully reconstructed Viking village and immerse yourself in the sights, sounds, and even smells of AD975. Located on the site of the famous Coppergate Dig, this museum offers a unique experience with interactive exhibits and an immersive ride through recreated Viking streets. Discover Norse mythology, Viking history, and a fascinating collection of artifacts including fossilized human poo.
name: JORVIK Viking Centre
address: 19 Coppergate, York, YO1 9WT, United Kingdom

excerpt: Railway history & artefacts, with 300 vehicles including steam world record holder, the Mallard.
detail_description: The National Railway Museum in York is a treasure trove of railway history and artifacts, featuring an impressive collection of over 300 vehicles, including the famous steam world record holder, the Mallard. Housed in the city's former train depot, this museum boasts the UK's largest collection of trains and rail-related memorabilia.
name: National Railway Museum York
address: Leeman Rd, York, YO26 4XJ, United Kingdom

excerpt: Victorian-era cobbled street recreated indoors with costumed guides, plus other exhibits.
detail_description: York Castle Museum, located in York, North Yorkshire, offers a unique and immersive experience for visitors to step back in time. The museum features a recreated Victorian street called Kirkgate, complete with authentic shops and costumed guides. It also showcases exhibits on everyday life from different eras, including the 1960s. With interactive displays and the use of modern technology to recreate historical settings, the museum provides an engaging look into York's past.
name: York Castle Museum
address: Tower St, York, YO1 9RY, United Kingdom

excerpt: 14th-century timber-framed structures overhang this landmark road, once home to many butcher shops.
detail_description: Shambles is a famous landmark in York, known for its 14th-century timber-framed buildings that used to house butcher shops. The street has a medieval feel with narrow cobblestone paving and crooked terraced houses, reminiscent of Diagon Alley from the Harry Potter movies. It's a popular spot for kids and Harry Potter fans, believed to have inspired Diagon Alley. The area is filled with charming gift shops, cafes, and boutiques.
name: Shambles
address: York, UK

excerpt: Tour exploring the history of chocolate & the city's confectioners, with a cafe & shop.
detail_description: Immerse yourself in the world of chocolate at York's Chocolate Story, an award-winning attraction located in the heart of the city. Join an interactive guided tour that delves into 4000 years of chocolate history, exploring York's confectionery past and present. Learn about the pioneers of the chocolate industry and iconic brands like Kit Kat and Aero. Indulge in delicious chocolate samples crafted by on-site chocolatiers and discover how to taste chocolate like a true Chocolatier.
name: York's Chocolate Story
address: King's Sq, York, YO1 7LD, United Kingdom

excerpt: 13th-century castle keep, built on a grass mound, formerly used as a prison & royal mint.
detail_description: Clifford's Tower, located in the heart of York, is a 13th-century castle keep perched on a grass mound. Originally part of York Castle built by William the Conqueror, it has served as a prison and royal mint before becoming a popular tourist attraction. Visitors can climb to the top for stunning panoramic views of the city and beyond to the North York Moors. The tower offers a glimpse into York's medieval past and is an excellent starting point for exploring the area.
name: Clifford's Tower, York
address: Tower St, York, YO1 9SA, United Kingdom

excerpt: Large gardens surrounding Yorkshire Museum, with mature trees, Roman ruins & a medieval abbey.
detail_description: Museum Gardens, located around the Yorkshire Museum, offer a blend of history and natural beauty. The museum itself houses collections covering archaeology, biology, astronomy, and geology with artifacts from the Viking and Roman periods. It also hosts workshops for children and community programs for adults. The botanical gardens boast a variety of trees, bulbs, and shrubs perfect for scenic walks or peaceful retreats.
name: Museum Gardens
address: Museum St, York, YO1 7FR, United Kingdom

excerpt: Remnants of a stonework enclosure around a rectangular fortification, erected in 71 CE.
detail_description: York City Walls are remnants of a stonework enclosure around a rectangular fortification, built in 71 CE. York has a rich history dating back to its founding in 71 AD as the capital of the Roman province in Britain. It later became famous for trade and commercial centers during the Middle Ages. The city developed into an important center for rail networks, manufacturing, education, and health services. Today, tourism plays a significant role in the local economy.
name: York City Walls
address: York, YO1 7LJ, United Kingdom

excerpt: Gallery featuring paintings & decorative arts from the 1400s to the present in an 1870s building.
detail_description: York Art Gallery is housed in an 1870s building and showcases a diverse collection of paintings and decorative arts spanning from the 1400s to contemporary pieces. The gallery also features interactive exhibits focusing on classic and contemporary art, making it a great destination for families, especially on rainy days. Additionally, the gallery offers workshops and special exhibitions worth exploring. With its fully accessible facilities including a cafe and family-friendly amenities, York Art Gallery provides an enriching experience for art enthusiasts of all ages.
name: York Art Gallery
address: Exhibition Square, York, YO1 7EW, United Kingdom

excerpt: A high-tech ghost house attraction with costumed characters & state-of-the-art scares.
detail_description: The York Dungeon is a thrilling and entertaining attraction in York that offers a unique way to explore the city's dark past. Visitors can expect to encounter costumed characters, state-of-the-art scares, and immersive sets as they journey through 2000 years of history. From infamous figures like Guy Fawkes and local witch Isabella Billington to the Vikings and the Plague, the experience brings York's terrifying history to life through ten live shows.
name: The York Dungeon
address: 12 Clifford St, York, YO1 9RD, United Kingdom

excerpt: Five galleries showcase archaeological treasures plus displays of rare animals, birds and fossils.
detail_description: Located in the Museum Gardens, the Yorkshire Museum features five galleries that display a wide array of archaeological treasures and rare animals, birds, and fossils. The museum's exhibitions offer a fascinating journey through history, including the Ryedale Hoard with Roman artifacts and a collection showcasing 150 million years of Yorkshire's history. Visitors can explore Roman artifacts, detailed regional history, Iron Age jewelry, extinct species, fossils, and notable pieces like the Viking sword and York Helmet.
name: Yorkshire Museum
address: Museum Gardens, Museum Street, York YO1 7FR, United Kingdom

excerpt: Traditional, mainstay tearoom offering formal afternoon teas or casual cafe dining on British fare.
detail_description: Betty's Café Tea Rooms is a renowned traditional tearoom that has been serving the people of York since 1936. Established by Swiss baker Fritz Butzer, it offers a choice between formal afternoon teas and casual cafe dining with British fare. The tearoom's interior was inspired by the Queen Mary ocean liner, providing an elegant setting for indulging in their famous Lady Betty Afternoon Tea.
name: Betty's Café Tea Rooms
address: 6-8 St. Helen’s Square, York, YO1 8QP, United Kingdom

excerpt: Restored former priory dating from 14th century, with high-ceilinged great hall & exposed timbers.
detail_description: Barley Hall, located in York, England, is a meticulously restored medieval townhouse dating back to the 15th century. The hall features high-ceilinged great halls and exposed timbers that provide an authentic glimpse into life during the medieval period. Visitors can immerse themselves in history through hands-on exhibits, antique furniture, paintings, audio and guided tours led by guides dressed in medieval costumes. Special events are also held throughout the year.
name: Barley Hall
address: 2 Coffee Yard, York, YO1 8AR, United Kingdom

excerpt: 1350s timber-framed building where merchants congregated, with museum exhibits & a cafe.
detail_description: The Merchant Adventurers' Hall, a remarkable timber-framed building dating back to the 1350s, stands as one of the oldest guildhalls in Great Britain. It holds historical significance as a hub for merchants engaging in pioneering business ventures that led to substantial wealth. The hall features a grand Great Hall with an oak-beam ceiling on the first floor and showcases its history as a hospital on the ground floor from the 14th to 20th centuries.
name: Merchant Adventurers' Hall
address: The Hall, Fossgate, York YO1 9XD, United Kingdom

excerpt: Imposing Georgian townhouse museum with significant collections of furniture, paintings and clocks.
detail_description: Fairfax House is an impressive Georgian townhouse museum located in the Micklegate area of York. It was designed by renowned architect John Carr in the 18th century for Lord Fairfax. The house has been meticulously restored to showcase the opulent lifestyle of a wealthy Georgian family, featuring a remarkable collection of furniture, paintings, and clocks from that era. Visitors can immerse themselves in the ambiance of the past and gain insight into life during this period.
name: Fairfax House
address: FairFax House, Castlegate, York YO1 9RN, United Kingdom

excerpt: Well-preserved house filled with 17th- and 18th-century furniture, ceramics, textiles and paintings.
detail_description: Located just north of York Minster, the National Trust-owned Treasurer's House is a well-preserved 17th-century residence filled with furniture, ceramics, textiles, and paintings. Originally built over a Roman road and later redesigned in the early 17th century, it showcases a mix of architectural styles. The house holds historical significance as the former residence of Frank Green, an influential figure in York.
name: National Trust - Treasurer's House, York
address: Minster Yard, York, YO1 7JL, United Kingdom

excerpt: Tours are offered of this historic home, built for the Lord Mayor in 1732 & still in use.
detail_description: York Mansion House, a historic home built in 1732 for the Lord Mayor, offers tours to visitors. It served as the civic heart of York for nearly 300 years and is an Instagram-worthy attraction on the outside and fascinating on the inside. The house features various rooms including staterooms, magnificent staircases, and a fully functional recreated 18th-century kitchen.
name: York Mansion House
address: St. Helen’s Square, York, YO1 9QL, United Kingdom

excerpt: Long established outdoor city center market open 7 days a week selling produce, crafts & clothing.
detail_description: Shambles Market is a well-established outdoor market located in the heart of York, open every day of the week. It offers a wide range of products including fresh produce, crafts, and clothing. The market has been recognized with the Best Outdoor Market award at the Great British Market Awards. Visitors can indulge in a culinary adventure at the dedicated food court where various food stands serve up delicious street food daily.
name: Shambles Market
address: 5 Silver St, York, YO1 8RY, United Kingdom

excerpt: Producing theatre with shows from new writing to classics and youth work, plus annual Mystery Plays.
detail_description: York Theatre Royal is a historic theater in York, established in 1744. It hosts a variety of shows from new writing to classics and youth work, including the annual Mystery Plays. The theater attracts audiences from all over England and tourists alike. In addition to York Theatre Royal, the city is home to other theaters such as Grand Opera House Theater and Joseph Rowntree Theater, making it an important hub for arts and literature.
name: York Theatre Royal
address: St Leonard's Pl, York, YO1 7HD, United Kingdom

excerpt: Flat race meetings from May-October, including a grandstand and restaurants with views of the track.
detail_description: York Racecourse hosts flat race meetings from May to October, offering a grandstand and restaurants with track views. The Vintage Christmas event in December features a marketplace celebrating 1930s-60s fashions and traditions. It's a great place for friends to enjoy dressing up, sipping drinks, and betting on horses. Notable events include The John Smiths Cup, Music Showcase Weekend, and the Welcome to Yorkshire Ebor Festival in October.
name: York Racecourse
address: Racecourse Road, Knavesmire Road, York YO23 1EX, United Kingdom

excerpt: Buzzing destination featuring bars & eateries in funky upcycled shipping containers.
detail_description: SPARK:York CIC is a vibrant outdoor destination in York, featuring a variety of bars and eateries housed in upcycled shipping containers. It's a hub for local start-ups, offering an eclectic assortment of food traders serving everything from bohemian cocktails to stacked burgers. The venue provides a laid-back and welcoming atmosphere for visitors to enjoy delicious street food and drinks.
name: SPARK York
address: 17-21 Piccadilly, York, YO1 9PB, United Kingdom

excerpt: Airy rooms, some with 4-poster beds, in a casual 16th-century pub offering a beer garden.
detail_description: The Golden Fleece York is a renowned 16th-century pub with airy rooms, some featuring 4-poster beds, and a charming beer garden. It is reputed to be the most haunted pub in York, boasting five spirits and even a real skeleton at the bar. The inn exudes history and charm, with wonky floors, dark bars, open fires, and ghost stories told in hushed tones over candlelit tables.
name: Golden Fleece York
address: 16 Pavement, York, YO1 9UP, United Kingdom

excerpt: Fallout monitoring centre in case of nuclear war until 1990s, now open and run by English Heritage.
detail_description: The York Cold War Bunker, operated by English Heritage, is a fascinating attraction that offers visitors a glimpse into the city's history. Tucked away in a quiet residential area, this former fallout monitoring center was in operation until the 1990s. Visitors can explore the underground facility, including the control center, dormitory, and staff room where volunteers once worked tirelessly to manage potential nuclear fallout.
name: York Cold War Bunker
address: Monument Cl, Holgate, York YO24 4HT, United Kingdom

excerpt: Archeology museum where children unearth replica historical finds in hands-on excavations.
detail_description: DIG: An Archaeological Adventure is an interactive museum where children can engage in hands-on excavations to unearth replica historical finds. Operated by the archaeologists behind York's Viking past and the Jorvik Viking Centre, this attraction offers a unique approach to history. With four active digging pits filled with artifacts from various eras, kids can experience the joy of discovery while learning about archaeological techniques.
name: DIG
address: DIG St Saviour Church, St Saviourgate, York YO1 8NN, United Kingdom

excerpt: Church dating back to the 11th century, now a contemporary gallery exhibiting art and installations.
detail_description: St Mary's Abbey, located in the Yorkshire Museum Gardens, is a historic church dating back to the 11th century. Once the wealthiest Benedictine abbey in Northern England, it was dissolved under Henry VIII in 1539. Despite much of its stone being removed over time, visitors can still see remnants of the nave wall and a section of the crossing adorned with stunning Gothic windows and tracery. The ruins offer a picturesque setting for a leisurely picnic among centuries-old history.
name: St Mary's Abbey
address: York, YO30 7DR, United Kingdom

excerpt: York is a walled city in northeast England that was founded by the ancient Romans. Its huge 13th-century Gothic cathedral, York Minster, has medieval stained glass and 2 functioning bell towers. The City Walls form a walkway on both sides of the River Ouse. The Monk Bar gate houses an exhibition tracing the life of 15th-century Plantagenet King Richard III.
detail_description: York, a historic walled city in northeast England, was established by the Romans and is home to the impressive 13th-century Gothic cathedral known as York Minster. The City Walls offer a scenic walkway along the River Ouse, while Monk Bar gate features an exhibition on the life of King Richard III. The city boasts excellent educational opportunities and modern amenities such as shops and restaurants. Additionally, it offers convenient rail connections and beautiful parks like Rowntree Park.
name: York
address: UK

detail_description: The Ghost Bus Tours offers an entertaining and informative tour of York with plenty of stops to see the city's most famous sights. The tour is short and easy to walk, making it great for families with young children.
name: The Ghost Bus Tours York
address: Station Rd, Bus stop RE, York, YO24 1AA, United Kingdom

excerpt: Theatre in a former 19th-century warehouse, hosting plays, musicals, opera, ballet and kids' shows.
detail_description: The Grand Opera House in York is a historic theater housed in a former 19th-century warehouse. It offers a diverse range of performances including plays, musicals, opera, ballet, and children's shows. As part of the Ambassador Theatre Group, it has become the largest fully operational theater in the county and is known for hosting touring productions of West End Musicals and Drama, Comedians, Opera & Ballet.
name: Grand Opera House
address: Clifford and, Cumberland St, York YO1 9SW, United Kingdom

detail_description: York Explore Library and Archive is a must-visit for history enthusiasts, offering public access to its archives with some requiring advance booking. The library garden is a tranquil spot featuring York's urban archaeology, displaying the city walls' development from Roman times. Families can enjoy the welcoming children's area and reasonably priced café, while book-loving visitors can browse through an extensive collection of books.
name: York Explore Library and Archive
address: Library Square, Museum St, York YO1 7DS, United Kingdom

detail_description: Discover the eerie and macabre history of York on The Bloody Tour of York, a ghost walk suitable for all ages. Led by a guide named Mad Alice, you'll stroll through streets and snickelways, hearing spooky tales of the Plague, infamous figures like Dick Turpin, and chilling stories of torture and execution.
name: The Bloody Tour of York
address: College St, York, YO1 7JF, United Kingdom

detail_description: Indulging in Afternoon Tea at The Grand is a delightful experience that perfectly encapsulates the essence of Yorkshire hospitality. Nestled within the stunning confines of this five-star hotel, which boasts an impressive blend of Edwardian elegance and modern luxury, guests are treated to a warm welcome from friendly staff. The Grand's rich history as the former headquarters of the North Eastern Railway Company adds to its charm, with original features and grand staircases creating an inviting atmosphere.
name: Afternoon Tea at The Grand
address: Station Rise, York, YO1 6GD, United Kingdom

detail_description: Embark on a fascinating and entertaining cruise along the River Ouse with City Cruises York - Kings Staith Landing. Whether you choose to sit on the open top deck or in the enclosed saloon, you'll have an excellent view of York's history and its connection to the River Ouse. Learn about how the river has shaped the city over time, from flooding to its role as an inland port.
name: City Cruises York - Kings Staith Landing
address: King's Staith, York, YO1 9SN, United Kingdom

detail_description: The River Ouse, accessible from York city center, offers a picturesque walk with opportunities to spot ducks, otters, and swans. Cycling along the river's cycle tracks is also popular, with the York solar system trail being a favorite. The river is adorned with restaurants, greenery, bridges, and river boats. Visitors can enjoy a pint at The Kings Arms pub or take a sightseeing cruise with entertaining commentary by local skippers.
name: River Ouse
address: Wellington Row, York, YO1 6HU, United Kingdom

excerpt: With a programme of musicals, national rock and pop bands and comedians, plus conference facilities.
detail_description: Located in the heart of York, York Barbican is the city's largest music and arts venue offering a diverse range of entertainment. From live music and comedy to sports events and children's activities, there is something for everyone. The venue hosts a variety of events including musical performances by renowned bands like The Waterboys, opera shows by the Ukrainian National Opera, and comedy nights featuring BBC Radio's award-winning panel show 'I'm Sorry I Haven't a Clue.'
name: York Barbican
address: Paragon St, York, YO10 4AH, United Kingdom

detail_description: Embark on a delightful adventure through York's city center with The York Cat Trail, featuring 20 charming cat statues waiting to be discovered. This unique walking trail offers a fun and engaging way to explore the city's attractions while searching for these adorable feline sculptures. Whether you're an avid cat lover or simply seeking a distinctive stroll, this trail promises an enjoyable challenge for all ages.
name: The York Cat Trail
address: 34 Coney St, York, YO1 9ND, United Kingdom

detail_description: Roots is a restaurant overseen by the acclaimed chef Tommy Banks, known for its seasonal farm-to-table tasting menu. Housed in a historic building from the 1800s, it celebrates its farming roots with a strong emphasis on local and seasonal produce, offering contemporary British cuisine. The restaurant is part of York's dynamic food scene, catering to both experimental food enthusiasts and those seeking comfort in French classics or Neapolitan pizza.
name: Roots
address: Theatre Royal, St Leonard's Pl, York YO1 7HD, United Kingdom

detail_description: Brew York is a popular craft brewery with multiple taprooms in Yorkshire, including one in Leeds. The York branch offers a vibrant atmosphere with an abundance of taps behind the bar and a weekly pub quiz. The brewery is known for its creative and innovative beers, such as the Brew York Imperial Tonkoko, a delicious coconut, tonka, cacao, and vanilla milk imperial stout.
name: Brew York
address: Unit 6, Enterprise Complex, Walmgate, York YO1 9TT, United Kingdom

excerpt: Shopping centre for discounts on international designer and high street fashion brands and homeware.
detail_description: Designer Outlet York, located in Fulford just a little further from York City Centre, is a haven for fashion enthusiasts seeking great deals on international designer and high street fashion brands as well as homeware. With over 120 major names like Calvin Klein, Boss, Adidas, Levis and Lacoste, shoppers can enjoy significant discounts of up to 50 or 60%. The beautifully landscaped garden setting adds to the charm of this top fashion and shopping destination.
name: Designer Outlet York
address: St Nicholas Ave, York, YO19 4TA, United Kingdom

detail_description: Stonegate is a captivating street that offers a journey through history. It follows the path of the ancient Roman road, Via Praetoria, which once connected to the Basilica, the heart of Roman military operations. As you stroll along this bustling shopping street, you'll uncover remnants of its rich past waiting to be explored.
name: Stonegate
address: York, UK

detail_description: Blossom Street Gallery in York is a charming space that offers a diverse range of art and gifts. The gallery features an array of prints, books, jewelry, stationery, cards, and wrapping paper created by independent artists and makers. Visitors can find affordable prints by renowned children's illustrators as well as local street scenes. The warm and welcoming atmosphere includes a blackboard wall for children to enjoy while adults browse the offerings.
name: Blossom Street Gallery
address: 2 Blossom St, York, YO24 1AE, United Kingdom

excerpt: Contemporary restaurant with a riverside terrace  and an all-day menu of Modern British dishes.
detail_description: Located in a picturesque spot by the River Ouse, The Star Inn The City is a popular restaurant offering modern British cuisine. With a diverse all-day menu that changes weekly to highlight seasonal ingredients, this brasserie-style eatery aims to bring the countryside's taste to the city. Inspired by Andrew Pern of the Michelin-starred Star Inn at Harome, it prides itself on using locally-sourced ingredients to create delectable dishes.
name: The Star Inn The City
address: Lendal Engine House, Museum St, York YO1 7DR, United Kingdom

excerpt: Relaxed bar with an extensive menu of inventive cocktails, plus smoothies, milkshakes & a gin shop.
detail_description: Evil Eye Lounge in York is a whimsical and enchanting bar that offers an extensive menu of creative cocktails, smoothies, and milkshakes. Tucked away on York's oldest street, this quirky gin shop and cocktail bar boasts unique decor and a vast selection of both classic and modern cocktails. The lounge's mystical and mischievous vibe creates a celestial experience for visitors, with mesmerizing wall decorations that inspire curiosity.
name: Evil Eye
address: 42 Stonegate, York, YO1 8AS, United Kingdom

excerpt: Locally sourced fare & house-baked sweets are served with craft coffee & tea drinks in hip digs.
detail_description: Brew & Brownie is a popular independent cafe located in the heart of York, just a short walk from the York Minster. The cafe is known for its delicious coffee and exquisite menu of sweet and savory treats made from seasonal, local, and quality ingredients. They also offer vegan and gluten-free options for their brunches.
name: Brew & Brownie
address: 5 Museum St, York, YO1 7DT, United Kingdom

detail_description: Skeldergate Bridge, a Victorian-era marvel, links York Castle to Baile Hill with its elegant arches and intricate ironwork. Reconstructed in the 1880s, it offers stunning views of the River Ouse. Travelers can stroll through its wide footpaths and dedicated cycling lanes. Adjacent Tower Gardens on the East shore provide a pleasant walk, while Dyls at the East end offers refreshments.
name: Skeldergate Bridge
address: River Ouse, York, United Kingdom

detail_description: The Visit York Information Centre & Gift Shop is a must-visit destination at the heart of the city. The friendly and knowledgeable team is ready to provide expert advice on attractions, travel tips, dining spots, shopping areas, and upcoming events to make your visit exceptional. They offer an extensive collection of complimentary information leaflets and guides for your convenience. Additionally, they provide free entry for various cardholders and individuals with valid proof.
name: Visit York Information Centre & Gift Shop
address: 21 Parliament St, York, YO1 8SG, United Kingdom

excerpt: Lively walking tour exploring Yorkshire history through its streets via folklore and spooky legends.
detail_description: York's Adventurous Ghost Walk guides you through the city's dark and eerie streets, sharing some of the city's most notorious ghost stories.
name: The Original Ghost Walk of York
address: Kings Arms, Ouse Bridge, King's Staith, York YO1 9SN, United Kingdom

excerpt: Mediterranean dishes served in an exposed-brick interior with lots of clocks set to 8 o'clock.
detail_description: Ate O'Clock is a charming restaurant located in York, offering a unique dining experience with its exposed-brick interior adorned with numerous clocks all set to 8 o'clock. The bistro-style spot serves a variety of Mediterranean and European-inspired dishes made from locally sourced ingredients. Whether you prefer indoor dining or the cozy courtyard, Ate O'Clock caters to all preferences, making it an ideal choice for date nights, gatherings with friends, or family meals.
name: Ate O'Clock
address: 13a High Ousegate, York, YO1 8RZ, United Kingdom

detail_description: Shambles Food Court is a bustling hub of local vendors offering a diverse range of fast food options, from fish and chips to gyros and burritos. Located near York's famous ancient street Shambles, this historic market has been injected with modern energy to create a charming outdoor space for social dining. The shared seating arrangement creates a lively atmosphere, making it the perfect spot to grab a quick bite while exploring the city.
name: Shambles Food Court
address: 5 Silver St, York, YO1 8RY, United Kingdom

detail_description: The York Roast Co. is a beloved dining spot in York, drawing both locals and visitors with its delectable range of meaty sandwiches, Yorkshire pudding wraps, and Sunday dinner-inspired meat boxes. With two locations in York and others in Chester, Salisbury, and Shrewsbury, this chain has gained popularity for its mouthwatering roasted carved sandwiches. The highlight of their menu is the famous Yorky Pud Wrap – a Yorkshire Pudding sandwich wrap that went viral.
name: The York Roast Co.
address: 4 Stonegate, York, YO1 8AS, United Kingdom
